comment.text:
You must go to this place if you were into fresh ingredients wonderful customer service and absolutely delicious meals at a very reasonable price. Danna at the counter Was super helpful as I've never been there before and friendly. Mike the owner was gracious and grateful for my business. 
I had a curry bowl with chicken that was perfectly cooked and very flavorful for only $11. Then I tried the boas That were soft Freschi fluffy steamed buns filled with so much deliciousness. Definitely going back to this place I'm so grateful to have this right around the corner and my local neighborhood of EAV. Keep up the great work guys

Food is always fresh and delicious EVEY SINGLE TIME my go to bao bun place in Atlanta.
 * also a plus that they are BLM supporters

My friend is a vegan. 

Despite my paleolithic preferences, I pressed myself to find a spot that could accommodate our group's differing tastes without compromising on the excitement of discovery. (Not everyone is excited to learn about curry tofu.)

The Venn Diagram overlaps and Mushi Ni appears! It's one stall in this hole-in-the-wall food court hallway, communal picnic tables lining the wall opposite their humble stand. We sat and enthusiastically studied the menu. Their specialty...is the bao.

I got a Com-Bao (a combo, y'all) which included one savory mushroom bao with a creamy garlic mayo that reminded me of a baby Philly cheesesteak and one cauliflower bang bang. 

Cauliflower is having a true Anne Hathaway moment: straighten this teenager's hair and take off her glasses and suddenly everyone's all "cauliflower, so cool!" By playing with its variable texture, making it crispy and keeping it juicy, Mushi Ni has made an irresistible sandwich/taco of spicy cauliflower. This shit is next level addictive. Both were vegan.

We all got different baos. My boyfriend got an octo-bao with lime aioli and it might have been the best-prepared octopus I've ever had. I let go of my ethical complications with eating octopus and, for the octo-bao, I'd do it again. Also extraordinary was the lemongrass-marinated pork belly with duck confit and plum hoisin sauce. HELLO? IS THIS THING ON?

It's all delicious. The four of us had at least 14 baos between us. To diversify, I also went with a spring mix and thin-sliced ribeye bowl. Simple yet tasty, filling and a great value. Imagine living around the block and needing a snack while your partner needs a full-blown meal. 

And then there was the Tempura Oreos, the kind of snack that kills your ego and makes the bottom of your belly glow. One of the owners, Michael Le, was serving us himself, swiping our cards with an iPad, behind him a deep fryer. His kindness, humor and hospitality resulted in an extra tempura oreo. 

They're local. They're organic. They're casual but not guilty or trashy, unique but accessible. What an exciting little spot. Go. I live 6 hours away and I'm mad about it.

I want more baos, Michael.

Mushi Ni is one of the restaurants inside the Global Grub Collective. They specialize in Asian baos and bowls, while using the "cleanest" ingredients possible (local, organic, pesticide-free, etc). 

I usually opt for their small bowls, which come with your choice of grain (brown rice, noodles, quinoa) or greens, and protein. The bulgogi is great, but I often will go for the mighty veggie option to keep it healthy. The veggie relish they include on it is delicious! The tokyo fries are also yummy. 

For the price, Mushi Ni is hard to beat. I also like there are lots of options here to go as healthy as you want, and it's quite vegan and vegetarian friendly.  Using quality local and organic ingredients is the cherry on top! I'm definitely a fan!

The place is nothing fancy but the food is EVERYTHING!! I can't get enough of their buns or baos. And their fried Oreos are such a chocolate indulgence. Their portions are generous and the prices are more than fair. They take care and pay attention to the details.

We wandered upon Mushi Ni while passing through Atlanta and I couldn't be happier that we found this place. My husband and I did the bao 6 pack, glass noodles, and pork buns. In the 6 pack bao we did 2 pork belly, beef bulgogi, tofu, duck confit and eggplant. When I tell you that pork belly bao was one of the best things I've eaten in a LONG time, I do not exaggerate. It was so crispy and juicy and just perfect. My next favorite was the eggplant. It rivaled the crispness of the pork belly and had incredible flavor! The pork buns were not what I expected, but still great. I wish I could have taken a picture of the glass noodles, but my husband inhaled them. I took a bite before he finished them off and I can confirm they are delicious! This place is definitely worth your while. Judging by the quality and flavor of our food, I'd say there isn't anything on the menu that would disappoint you.
The best Bao I have ever tried, extreme fluffy and soft. The kimchi dumplings were so crispy and tasty.

photos.caption: Kimichi & Veggie Dumplings, Cauliflower Bao, and Fries.
Soft shell crab bowl with fried rice.

comment.text:
Friendly, wonderful owners. 

A great mix of bao choices for carnivores and vegetarians (they even have one using Impossible Burger).

Tokyo Fries. Get them. 

In the best food hall in Atlanta - The Global Grub Collective. 

I hope to see them here for a while or even with their own location (if that's their goal).

Fantastic addition to EAV's little foodie haven.
This has become a regular go to for me. I appreciate their wide range of vegan options and their curbside pickup. Everything is tasty!

This place is soooo good! The curbside pickup is pretty convenient. My boyfriend and I had to walk to the storefront and ring the bell to get our food. They don't bring the food to you. We got the 6-pack bao buns, rice bowl, and duck confit fries. The baos are totally worth it. Even the vegetarian options. The rice bowl is a pretty healthy option and complemented the heavy richness of the duck confit fries. The brown rice in the bowl was too mushy for my taste. The duck confit fries are very sweet and savory simultaneously. It would have been difficult for to finish the fries without the rice bowl.
I ordered the Bao meal with cauliflower and Beyond meat, side of Tokyo fries. Extra sweet chili soy. DELICIOUS. I will definitely be back!!!

I'm at Mushi Ni nearly every week. Their food is absolutely fantastic and, as a vegan, I'm especially grateful that they have so many options. Among their vegan options are:
-4 types of bao
-veggie bowl
-veggie curry bowl with roti
-kimchi vegetable dumplings
-DEEP FRIED OREOS (minus the sauce)

I've taken several visitors here and they all love it. The staff are also very nice and just great people.

I'm on a journey to eat something new every week and Mushi Ni doesn't disappoint! I grabbed a cauliflower bao thinking I wouldn't like it but boy did my taste buds go on a delightful ride!! The cauliflower is seasoned with delight, the dough is fluffy and filling. I'm happy to have stepped out of my comfort zone. The shop is located in a tight spot but the process to order is smooth. If there's time and room, stay and enjoy the company. With picnic table seating, you're certain to make a friend

Excellent food. Great combinations of fusion to chose from. Made fresh and prompt. Friendly service and the most important....food is phenomenal. A must try in the multiple choice food heaven of we suki suki.
Super cool location and food court feel. Great for a causal lunch. Freely locals to dine with. The owner was amazingly friendly.

Make sure you look at the photos, because the outside sign does not say Mushi Ni. I couldn't find it the first time I visited the restaurant, but I decide to come back again and I am SO glad I did. The bao was soft and perfect. The fillings are well seasoned and well portioned. The duck fries and glass noodles are TO DIE FOR! I'm so glad I tried again to find the restaurant!
Ok so the food is good. It's $11 for three baos which is a little pricey but not terrible. I enjoyed the chicken and duck bao the most and if I were to ever be in the area again I'd get those two.

I came in today for lunch because of all of the positive reviews. As I stood at the table waiting to place an order, I saw the cook taste the food with his mixing spoon and then continued stirring the food with the same spoon. I walked right out of the door. Sir, this is not your home kitchen. That's absolutely disgusting AND there is a pandemic right now.

This is some of the best food in Atlanta. Every time I go I try to eat something new and I have never once been disappointed. Their food is amazing. Also their vegan/vegetarian options are very, very good. Their vegan dumplings are the best fried dumpling I've had in Atlanta... not the best vegan dumpling... the BEST dumpling. I love getting their classic bowl with sweet potato glass noodles and broccoli/kale mix (this broccoli /kale mix is so delicious and flavorful I eat it first and I eat all of it... and there's a LOT), topped with either duck confit, cauliflower or their lobster hash. Their pork belly bao is one of my favorite things I've ever put in my mouth. Really... EVERYTHING they make is good. Order the whole menu. You won't regret a visit.

Very good. Nice people. Eclectic soda choices.
A great lunch if you're looking for variety.

Must say that Mushi Ni is such a beautiful place. The rates are pretty moderate as well. Most everything I've tried so far have been really great. Their staff members were all so pleasant and attentive. I would come back to this place.
So good and so filling. The kimchi fries are delish and could be shared if you end up getting 3 baos like we did haha
Amazing service and fantastic food! Fast, delicious, affordable!!!!! We got the fries, caulipower cakes, and beef bao!!

Both my husband and I have been enjoying everything created at Mushi Ni for almost a year now and they still manage to impress our taste buds. So much thought is put into every single dish created and the outcome is astounding! Seriously, if you haven't tried them you are missing out.

photos.caption: Duck Confit Roti Roll. Drool worthy
The curry with beef and roti is comfort in a bowl. Phenomenal!

comment.text: Stopped at the collective for the first time in a while and was excited to see they had a Bao vendor. I had the shrimp and eggplant. The shrimp was superb!!!! Must try! He had some teaser smore baos on display! Hoping to try some next time.

Literally everything is delicious and I am saying this from personal experience of eating the entire menu. My favorites are the cauliflower bao (get two! TRUST ME) and the bowl with pork and ginger rice (done to perfection, crispy and juicy) but y'all. The sesame tempura fries with duck confit. It keeps me up at night. The fries are super crispy with a thicker, flavored coating then topped with duck confit and a katsu type sauce. It will wreck you emotionally. All of the team is super nice and friendly and it's all made fresh! Check it out and get the online pickup on their website, it's usually pretty quick

Stopped by here for amazing bao sandos before seeing some music down the street. I'm visiting Atlanta, and this was probably my favorite food I had the entire time I was here, and it was also some of the most affordable. Definitely give it a try!

I can't overstate how thrilled I am that EAV has such a cool, vibrant food hall as the Global Grub Collective.  I cherish the place and the SO and I wander in a couple of times a month.  And when we do, Mushi Ni is usually my first choice, because their boas are just so goddamn delicious.  Like, I think about them, I crave them, I am in a relationship with the frequent thought of their consumption--there's a new part of me now that can only be fulfilled by a Mushi Ni boa sampler and some crispy, piping hot sesame fries.  It's like I'm in love.  And you should be, too.  Believe me, it's so easy to enhance your life in this small but meaningful way.  

The bulgogi boa is my current favorite, a perfectly proportioned saucy and crisp little meat treat suspended inside a light boa cloud that steams delightful umami essence up into your thrilled little nostrils.  Everything about it bangs so hard, yet it is so soft and perfect.  The same could be said about all of their boas really.  The octopus and cauliflower are also favorites, but you should definitely get the sampler because they rotate through recipes and try new stuff all the time.  Go hungry and double your fun by getting some tasty glass noodles.

Check these guys out.  Mushi Ni is the real deal.  Everything is fresh and made on the spot, so make sure to tip well.

Just look at that menu. Such bao diversity! I rarely see so many distinct bao options, let alone so many vegetarian options... let alone at these un-bao-lievable prices.

I didn't try any bowls in my first visit and went with 3 bao. All flavorful  and juicy  .

I plan to come back next time I'm in town, but wouldn't be surprised to see this place expand and move.

Same with Lifting Ramen right next to Mushi Ni!

photos.caption: 3-Bao combo including mushroom bao, duck confit bao, and bulgogi bao ( bao sampler)

comment.text: Great little spot for Asian comfort food. Menu has baos,bowls,dumplings,etc highly recommend the duck confit bao- juicy and tender. Flavors are great. Prices are very reasonable.

Went into We Suki Suki to get something else but noticed Mushi Ni and had to check it out because I LOVE BAOS.  

I tried the pork belly and shrimp tempura baos.  Shrimp was crispy and pork belly was flavorful. I'm a sucker for all things pork belly so that was my fave but both were super tasty. The baos were some of the best I've had in Atlanta. 

I don't usually check out places on a whim but maybe I should more often because I'm so glad I found Mushi Ni. Next time I'll come specifically for Mushi Ni and check out the other items on their menu! Great addition to We Suki Suki!

The best beyond fries ever!  Great alternatives. I came here as a non-vegan two years ago and the buns are so soft and delicious. They don't give a small portion of beyond meat either. Very generous servings and it's super filling. Love the service here also!

Yes! This place is the real deal. It is a food counter in the midst of a small global food court (not to be confused with the food court at the mall) with a few other delicious looking menus. There is a row of picnic tables to sit at, lending to the possibility of sharing a seat with somebody you don't know. But don't let your introvert tendencies prevent you from missing this gem, the food is worth it. The staff is also exceedingly kind and patient.
I got the FilAM chicken as well as the bulgogi bao. Both were pretty amazing. Others in my group got the shrimp bao and were equally impressed. My side of Tokyo fries was the best batch of fries I've ever had. They are well-seasoned and served with an incredible Japanese mayo dipping sauce. My wife got the char siu bao side. Also delicious. My daughter had the veggie dumplings (think egg roll filling in a fried dumpling). Again, really tasty.
One recent reviewer mentioned a "greasy mess". Eh, maybe. I did not experience the same, but the fryer does factor prominently in the cooking of many of the dishes here, so if that is a big consideration for you, choose one of the other options in the same food court. For me, I'll eat the delicious food here and then choose an appropriate dinner.

Mushi Ni is tucked away in Suki Suki grub collective and is a fan favorite restaurant in East Atlanta Village. This grub collective concept is a shared flexible space that allows customers to try a wide variety of foods that are all in close proximity of each other. Each restaurant has very simple menus, but are held to a very high standard. Our destination today is known for its Baos, which are Chinese bread rolls stuffed with a assortment of meats and vegetables . Co-owners Michael and Chef Tanya Jimenez-Le, graduate of the Culinary Institute of America and prior chef at Gordon Ramsay`s two Michelin Star restaurant in New York, continue to provide great service and phenomenal dishes to their patrons. 
Meal started off great with a roti as an appetizer. Nicely breaded crispy shell made biting into it amazing. The Beef and  paired well with the sweet and mild sauce served on the side. 
Entree consisted of Chicken loganisa and Pork Belly Baos. The Baos were very fluffy but were offset by the crunchiness of the wonton noodles. The chicken and Pork was nicely seasoned and paired well with the fries. A side of spicy mayo added a nice kick to both the Baos and Fries. 
I was surprised at the end with Tempura fried double stuffed Oreos that laid in front of me. They were lightly breaded and served with Nutella and powdered sugar drizzled on top. I could not finish them as you can clearly see.That finished off the  nicely and I appreciate Michael for the kind gesture. Thank you again Michael and Chef Tanya for the wonderful meal and service! See you soon Mushi Ni!

Tried Mushi Ni last night for the first time, and as cheesy as this sounds, it will definitely not be my last time. I had the beef bulgogi bao, chop suey fried rice bowl with the cauliflower and tofu, and then the shrimp hakao. All of it was amazing!!!

Amazing - I actually had the hardest time finding this place as I didn't spend enough time looking through the reviews to tell me it was inside We Suki Suki!  And then searching through the stalls was tight - but the food?  Oh, awesome.  I come from an Asian food desert (Sorry Columbus, Ohio, you are getting better.) so baos are in short supply at home.  I was not hungry, so I chose one - and it was delicious.  So good - drippy, yummy, texturally interesting, and everything dear to my heart.  Don't look for bland mushy stuff here!

Amazing food. The buns were scrumptious and the Tokyo fries were beyond delicious with the bang sauce. Whenever I'm in the mood for something a little different than my normal fare, Mushi Ni is the place
Wow the food was so good and service was quick. Highly recommend. I will definitely be back to try more from the menu

photos.caption: Beef Bulgogi and pork belly baos with dumplings

comment.text:
Mushi is the best place ever and the owners are everything.
Ever since they opened I have been continously wowed by their constant adventrous creations and deliciousness.
They specialize in The Bao....and every one I have ever had has been mouth watering. They also have so many creative vegetarian options....the sweet potato noodles sooo yummy...and the cauliflower cakes...kill it!!!
Cant get enough.!!!!
And the owners are a husband wife dynamic duo of peaceful passion and love...I love it here....
Go see them and treat yo self

Extremely flavorful food and amazing vegan options. 
I got the beyond meat, cauliflower, and mushroom bao with the tempura fried Oreos. Everything was perfect. 
Really easy social distanced take out or he will bring it to your car with the no contact option.

This place is overhyped. We ordered Bao six pack with (shrimp, duck, pork belly, bulgogi, chicken and eggplant) and Tokyo fries. Baos are good but not outstanding. They all tastes the same. Both baos and fries were greasy. Easy parking across the street.
Holy. Crap. Y'all. This food is amazing. Delicious. Bulgogi everything. Bao is BEAUTIFUL. Tokyo fries but also dip them in the roti sauce. I'm so happy. Best Valentine's Day dinner ever.

Ordered online. The baobuns were excellent, just wished that the experience of getting the food to my car wasn't so complicated. Parking in that area is confusing to me. They were also 20 minutes late in getting the order ready, even though I had placed the order over an hour before pick up time.

Place is absolute . We had the pork buns and the bao sampler and I think it's my new favorite place in Atlanta. You can do quick take out or sit down. Eating there is a bit cramped and probably not meant for going to a "sit down dinner", but for quick bites on the go you really can't beat this. Amazing!
I love this place . 1 because the food is sooo good . 2. They have a whole menu for vegan / Vegetarian food. 3. The price is on point. I would highly recommend this place.
Amazing boas with so many vegan options on the menu. It's a little hole in the wall that never disappoints

The food was outstanding never really would have stopped here except for all the great reviews. Once you get past the layout and the fact they have picnic tables for seating you'll be in store for some really awesome food.   I plan on going back for sure.  I have the chop Suey garlic and ginger rice with the nightly vegetables. Tofu and fried cauliflower.  Let me tell you the cauliflower was incredible and I will try it as an appetizer next time.

The food is delicious and the staff was super helpful and friendly. I ate there with my husband and our infant daughter around 6 on a Friday. Good scene for kids, better for parents bc the food is great. We just arrived in atl from atx and were really hungry, ordered the tokyo fries, the cauliflower and the vietnamese pork baos and a scallion pancake with duck. Have I said it enough? The food was really good.

photos.caption: My kid clearly had her mind blown

comment.text: Places was amazing! Although the place is pretty small the food makes up for it. I've tried the ramen poke bowls and now the baos. Every place has been delicious.

My first impression of Mushi Ni was via delivery which is always scary. They had my order read fast and it arrived hot! The baos were killer!!! We had the chicken, tofu, and cauliflower baos they were all equally as flavorful!! The bowl was awesome the greens were fresh and the noodles had so much flavor. I was especially surprised by how much I enjoyed the tempura Oreos... I originally ordered these for my kids but I lovedddd them. My kids loved the fries and chicken baos.... they can be hard to please so we will definitely be ordering from here again. Overall awesome experience.
